It is to be noted that the entire computation is carried out in the normalized axial coordinate ξ(=x/L). The space part of the dynamic displacements are approximated in the normalized coordinate as (9a)wx(ξ)≅∑i=1 nwciφi(ξ) (9b)ux(ξ)≅∑i=nw+1 nw+nuciαi-nw(ξ) where ϕi and αi denote the sets of orthogonal admissible functions for wx and ux, respectively, nw and nu denote the number of functions for wx and ux, respectively, and ci represents the set of unknown coefficients. The start function for wx is selected to satisfy the admissible flexural boundary conditions of the beam, and is listed in Table 1 for different boundary conditions. The necessary start function for ux is selected to satisfy the admissible in-plane boundary conditions of the beam, which is given by α1=ξ(1-ξ). The higher order orthogonal functions are generated numerically from the start functions using the Gram Schmidt orthogonalization scheme. Table 1.
Start functions for displacement wx
Boundary condition φ1(ξ)
CC {ξ(1-ξ)}2
SS {sin(πξ)}
CS {ξ2(3-5ξ+2ξ2)}
CF {ξ2(6-4ξ+ξ2)}
CC: clamped–clamped, SS: simply supported–simply supported, CS: clamped–simply supported, CF: clamped–free.

The sets of admissible functions ϕi and αi for wx and ux remain the same as those used for the forced vibration analysis. Substituting the expressions of strain energy and potential energy in Equation (13), and using the displacement fields given by Equation (9), the set of governing equations for this case is obtained in the form given below:
(14)[K]{c}={f}
where [K] and {f} are the stiffness matrix and load vector, respectively. The form and the elements of [K] and {f} remain the same as those given for the forced vibration analysis, provided in Section 2.1. The similarities arise from the fact that Equation (10) also describes the equilibrium of the dynamic system, executing forced vibration, at the peak load level of harmonic excitation. Equation (14) is nonlinear in nature and solved by the direct substitution technique with a successive relaxation scheme. The solution of Equation (14) provides the statically imposed displacement fields of the beam, which is used in solving the dynamic problem, where the free vibration frequencies are determined at its deflected configuration.
